Anonymous Tue 13 Dec 2022 03:35:21 No.52993483 Report

>>52993074
It's a bullpup. That big rectangular slot is where the case ejects--it looks like the ejection port of a semiauto, and most firearms in this category are bolt action, but I can let that slide. The problem with this arrangement is that you can shoot a rifle like that right-handed only. It ejects cases out of that port, into the left side of your head, if you shoot it off the left shoulder. Of course if it's a bolt action and manually operated, you have the option of tilting the gun away and manipulating it to eject the case manually. If it's semiauto, a .50 cal set up that way would brain you with a two and a half pound chunk of brass that's not quite incandescent and moving with considerable force.

Bullpup designs are one of several design compromises that exist in the present day. Small arms design hasn't really advanced significantly in seventy-five years or so. There are different arrangements, different engineering tradeoffs, but there are no magical propellants that are significantly more efficient than the ones that existed back in the era of vacuum tubes--none that can be economically mass produced, anyway. No magical materials have been created that allow significantly lighter weight or greater strength or durability, etc., and if anything postwar changes putting greater emphasis on lightweight materials and high precision have resulted in less durable tools. It's rather humbling when you think about it.

Well, one thing that blocks development is that we're at peak understanding of modern metallic cartridge weapons and that they're good enough. There were the several attempts during the Cold War to create new weapons, because that's when a conflict was looming where equipping your army with a weapon that gives them an edge could mean the difference between winning and losing.
